<TEXT>
<P>
 DUTCH MODERNE: Graphic Art From De Stijl to Deco by Steven Heller & Louise 
Fili (Chronicle Books: $16.95; 132 pp., paperback original). Heller's 
attractive survey of graphic design between the wars continues with this 
examination of Dutch logos, posters, advertisements and magazine covers. The 
tension between the adherents of the more eclectic, decorative Wendigen style 
and the more formal De Stijl (the style) produced a strikingly diverse body of 
work. Although equally elegant, many of these designs appear less angular than 
their American or French counterparts. 
</P>
