<HEADLINE>
<P>
FOUR-STAR MOVIES; 'THE BEST YEARS OF OUR LIVES' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kevin Thomas 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 William Wyler's 1946 film from Robert Sherwood's script struck a deep and 
lasting note in audiences. It masterfully tells of the homecoming from World 
War II of several very different men living in the same small city and who face 
challenges adjusting to civilian life.They are banker Frederic March (left), 
soda jerk Dana Andrews (right) and nice guy Harold Russell, who now has hooks 
where his arms and hands used to be and is afraid to face his fiancee (Cathy 
O'Donnell). The great homecoming scene between March and Myrna Loy, who plays 
his wife, was inspired by Wyler's own return to his wife, the late Margaret 
Tallichet. With Teresa Wright (pictured), Virginia Mayo and Hoagy Carmichael 
(AMC Sunday 6 and 11 p.m.). 
</P>
<P>
 Other selected four-star movies this week: 
</P>
<P>
 Moonstruck Cinemax, Sunday, 6:30 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
 The Gunfighter Cinemax, Sunday, noon 
</P>
<P>
