<HEADLINE>
<P>
CRITICS' PICKS: 'GUNCRAZY' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kenneth Turan 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 No matter how often we've seen it, if it's done right -- as this 1992 film was 
-- there's something endlessly watchable about violence-prone young lovers 
fighting off a fatalistic universe. Borrowing its title (here shortened to one 
word) and some broad concepts from Joseph Lewis's 1949 film noir classic and 
"Bonnie and CLyde," first-time director Tamra Davis and writer Matthew Bright 
have brought an empathetic approach to this latest version.Its small central 
California town setting is so drab and listless that many of its males view 
16-year-old Anita (Drew Barrymore, right, with Ione Skye) as their primary 
source of entertainment. Anita is a study in isolation and despair when she 
begins a pen-pal relationship with an equally bereft prisoner (James LeGros) 
who has a violent past (Showtime Thursday at 10:05 p.m.). Kenneth Turan 
</P>
