<HEADLINE>
<P>
MOTHERS & SONS; PEOPLE: PROFESSIONALS WHO FOLLOW IN THEIR PARENT'S FOOTSTEPS 
RANGE FROM A FRENCH RESTAURATEUR IN NEWPORT BEACH TO A LAGUNA BEACH REALTOR. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ANNE MICHAUD, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 To Orange County, he is a provider of gracious French dining. To his mother, 
he is her "petit chou" -- little cabbage, a common term of endearment in 
France. 
</P>
<P>
 Therese Olhats journeyed from France to Newport Beach for the first time last 
week to witness the success of her 40-year-old son, Pascal, and his restaurant 
of the same name. There he uses the lessons of French country cooking learned 
in his mother's kitchen in Normandy. The two prepared a Norman feast together 
for restaurant diners on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
 But as most sons and daughters do at times, Olhats chafes at his mother's 
tendency to see him as not quite grown up. His return visits to France don't 
help: "I sit in the same seat at the table and eat the same food as I did 20 
years ago," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 For sons to follow in their mothers' footsteps is a trend still in its 
infancy. Logic -- and several experts -- suggests that such dynasties will 
become fairly common before long, because women have been starting businesses 
at twice the rate of men in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
 Statistically, however, mother-son teams are rather unusual, said Jon Goodman, 
director of USC's entrepreneur program, "because we're in the first generation 
where women in significant numbers are managing businesses. But I think we will 
see more of them in time."  
</P>
<P>
 Goodman has the numbers on her side. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Women now own slightly more than a third of the businesses in the United 
States, according to the National Assn. of Women Business Owners. The group 
also found that an estimated 6.5 million women-owned companies together employ 
more people than all of the Fortune 500 combined. 
</P>
<P>
 Among more than 600 family-owned companies surveyed last year by the Gallup 
Organization for Massachusetts Mutual Life Insurance Co., 46% reported that a 
son was actively involved in the business. The survey did not differentiate 
between a father and mother as the business owner. 
</P>
<P>
 There are tremendous rewards to be had from mother and son sharing a vocation. 
</P>
<P>
 "I am very proud of Pascal and his wife," Therese Olhats said in French, as 
tears came to her eyes. "They have a lot of ambition and have worked very 
hard." 
</P>
<P>
 "It's thanks to her education," her son replied, becoming choked up himself. 
</P>
<P>
 The kitchen is a time-honored realm where sons can follow in their mothers' 
footsteps. In other professions, the mother-son combination is rare, but it is 
becoming less so, experts say, as women move en masse into the roles of 
professional and entrepreneur. 
</P>
<P>
 There are, of course, famous exceptions. Mary Martin, who played Peter Pan on 
Broadway, and her actor son, Larry Hagman, the J.R. Ewing of "Dallas" fame. 
Cosmetics whiz Mary Kay Ash and her son, Richard R. Rogers, who now runs the 
company. Helen and David Copley of Copley Newspapers, which publishes, among 
others, the San Diego Union-Tribune. 
</P>
<P>
 Locally, Zee Allred and son Dean run a national swimming pool supplies 
business, Pool Water Products in Irvine, which employs 350 people. And Turner 
Associates Realtors in Laguna Beach embraces the talents of three generations 
-- from its founder to her grandson. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 The combination can be a powerful one, said Jacqueline Freiberg, director of 
the University of San Diego Family Business Institute. It captures the 
strengths of both genders to compete fiercely yet form close, lasting 
relationships with customers and suppliers. And it avoids the rivalries that 
can arise in mother-daughter, father-son or husband-wife business teams. 
</P>
<P>
 "Moms who run businesses are probably self-sufficient, secure and 
independent," Freiberg said. "It's a sweet opportunity to work with someone you 
not only love, but respect." 
</P>
<P>
 Louise Turner Arnold founded Turner Associates in 1964. She has a strong 
handshake, a direct gaze and a bright red blazer. It is difficult to describe 
her without using the word "zip." 
</P>
<P>
 Arnold said it was unusual for a woman to open her own real estate business in 
the mid-1960s. But she has been well-accepted in the role, she said, with one 
memorable exception: a fellow realtor who was showing a client one of Arnold's 
homes. 
</P>
<P>
 "He thought he knew everything, and I knew nothing," she said. "But I made the 
sale, so it didn't really matter, did it?" 
</P>
<P>
 Arnold's daughter, Nancy Turner Casebier, joined the company in 1975 when her 
youngest child was 4 years old. Nancy's oldest child, Kevin Casebier, joined 
the company right after college in January, 1990. He had planned to help with 
the firm's summer rental business, but he is now making a career in real 
estate. 
</P>
<P>
 The three share the commissions of their individual sales; another 30 agents 
work from the Turner office, which specializes in luxury homes. 
</P>
<P>
 Kevin Casebier said he brings a valuable male perspective to the business. 
From time to time, a buyer who appears quite wealthy and serious will take a 
real estate agent through all the steps of purchasing a home, then vanish. 
</P>
<P>
 Recently, Casebier spotted one of these phony buyers. "I saw through him, that 
we were wasting our time," he said. "I think I spotted him faster than my 
mother or grandmother would have." 
</P>
<P>
 Nancy Casebier said she prefers the generational ties to working with a 
spouse. "This way, it's not directly competitive at home," she said. "My mother 
wants me to excel, and I want Kevin to excel." 
</P>
<P>
 Besides, Arnold added, two people in the same house with a realtor's 
seven-day-a-week schedule could be maddening. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Zee Allred can attest to the hurried pace that comes with a husband-and-wife 
business. She began her company with her husband, and their two sons spent many 
afternoons, summer vacations and spring breaks from college helping out. 
</P>
<P>
 "Beginning when they were about 6 or 7 years old, I would pick them up from 
school and take them to the office with me," she said. "So, they grew up with a 
working mother." 
</P>
<P>
 Her younger son, Dean, 42, is now president of the national pool distribution 
company, and Allred is chief operating officer. 
</P>
<P>
 Her older son left the business 10 years ago to start his own in Houston, 
doing the same thing. During the past three years, as Allred's company expanded 
to become a nationwide business, the two actually became competitors. She 
bought him out in December. 
</P>
<P>
 Though the competitive relationship existed, Allred sees it through a mother's 
eyes. 
</P>
<P>
 "I think he wanted to experience his own time of being in business for 
himself," she said. "I thought that was a great idea." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Meta Strandberg is another mother who sees her son as "wonderful." Strandberg, 
70, lives and gardens in the Swedish countryside, throwing herself into the 
hobby that is her passion from mid-April to the end of September. 
</P>
<P>
 Strandberg is a pioneer of organic gardening, having published a classic 
how-to manual in 1974 that has been translated from Swedish into five other 
languages. Roughly translated, its title is "Farming Without Poisons." She has 
written nine other books on food, including a vegetable cookbook that is 
available in Dutch, German and English. 
</P>
<P>
 Her son is Ulf Anders Strandberg, head chef of Gustaf Anders, the popular 
Swedish restaurant at South Coast Plaza Village in Santa Ana. The eatery's name 
comes from Strandberg's middle name and that of his partner, Bill Gustaf 
Magnuson. 
</P>
<P>
 The restaurant makes seven or eight kinds of bread daily, from coarse, 
unrefined grains, Strandberg said. "That is the big connection between my 
mother's ideas and my own," he said. "The importance of good bread." 
</P>
<P>
 As a small boy, Strandberg was interested in colors, materials and design, his 
mother said. He showed a love of artistry that she believes expressed itself 
ultimately in his cooking. 
</P>
<P>
 "Maybe I inspired him, just by being interested in food myself," she said. 
"But I never chose (a career) for him." 
</P>
<P>
 The passion for food runs in the family. Both of Strandberg's sisters are 
excellent cooks, their mother said, although they do not cook professionally.  
</P>
<P>
 Strandberg went to culinary school, but then he actually followed his father's 
career for about 10 years, working for a computer firm until he was in his 
early 30s. He ran into one of Stockholm's premier restaurateurs, Carl Butler, 
and began helping him in the restaurant from time to time. 
</P>
<P>
 The experience recalled his early love of elaborate family feasts. "In Sweden, 
there is not much else to do on the dark, cold winter nights but eat," he said, 
joking. 
</P>
<P>
 He and a partner opened a restaurant in Pacific Beach in San Diego, then moved 
to La Jolla. Henry Segerstrom, also of Swedish descent, invited the pair to 
move their operation to South Coast Plaza Village. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's a pity" that they live so far apart, Meta Strandberg said. 
</P>
<P>
 Therese Olhats said she feels the same way. In the early days, she used to say 
to him, "Have a restaurant, but save a small corner for me to cook in," her son 
recalled. 
</P>
<P>
 That dream came true last week for the first time. 
</P>
<P>
 Behind the country-patterned fabrics and bouquets of pink, peach and white 
roses, Therese and Pascal Olhats cooked apple pieces in Calvados, a sweet, 
strong apple liqueur made in the Normandy region. 
</P>
<P>
 Therese Olhats said that her son followed her around in the kitchen when he 
was a boy, tasting and learning. Pascal Olhats said he hopes that one of his 
three daughters will one day enter the profession. 
</P>
<P>
 "I won't force them, though," he said. "It must come from the inside, this joy 
in eating. Not everyone has it. It's a passion." 
</P>
</TEXT>
