<P>
COUNTYWIDE FOCUS: THOUSAND OAKS; HOUSE BLAZE CAUSES $105,000 IN DAMAGES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SCOTT HADLY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A two-alarm fire caused an estimated $105,000 in damage to a Thousand Oaks 
home about noon Saturday, a Ventura County Fire Department spokeswoman said. 
</P>
<P>
 The fire began in the attic of the garage and spread into the west wing of the 
home, according to the spokeswoman, who said investigators had not discovered a 
cause. 
</P>
<P>
 Mark Koenig, 25, who lives in the house with his mother, said he was heading 
home on a lunch break from his job as a car wash attendant when he was passed 
by firefighters. 
</P>
<P>
 "I saw this big plume of smoke and said, 'Wow it looks like something near my 
house is on fire,' " he said. 
</P>
<P>
 When he arrived, firefighters were already pouring water on the blazing garage 
as the fire spread into the house. 
</P>
<P>
 "I commend (the firefighters) for doing a good job. They saved this half of 
the house," Koenig said, pointing to the undamaged east side of the home. 
</P>
<P>
 It took firefighters about 40 minutes to douse the blaze, the spokeswoman 
said. No one was injured, she said. SCOTT HADLY 
